<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>THE PLAINTIFF/APPELLANT APPEALS to the Court of Appeal from the costs decision of the Honourable Justice Markus Koehnen (the &ldquo;Application Judge&rdquo;) dated March 3, 2018 made at Toronto.</P>
<P>THE APPELLANT ASKS that the costs award granted by the Application Judge be set aside with costs.</P>
<P>THE GROUNDS FOR THE APPEAL are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The Respondents were awarded costs of $60,583.05 arising from a failed application to assess the fees of the Respondents;</P>
<P>2. The Application Judge erred in law in holding that the costs awarded a self-represented litigant should be &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;, as opposed to &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;, contrary to the binding decision of the Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF>;</P>
<P>3. The Application Judge further erred in law in permitting evidence of opportunity costs to be introduced by way of Reply, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Friends of Lansdowne v. Ottawa</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 1015</CITE><PARANUM>56</PARANUM></CASEREF>;</P>
<P>4. The Application Judge further erred in law in awarding a self-represented litigant partial indemnity costs at exactly the same rate as would be awarded against a losing party who was not self-represented, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC><CITE>[1999] O.J. No. 4600</CITE><COURTJUR>C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>;</P>
<P>5. The Application Judge further erred in awarding the Respondent opportunity costs without requiring him to demonstrate that the work performed could not have been done on weekends or evenings, contrary to the principle articulated in <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE></CASEREF>, where the court held that evidence of lost personal time does not amount to an opportunity cost;</P>
<P>6. The Application Judge's findings conflict with binding appellate jurisprudence;</P>
<P>7. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. Rule 62.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
<P>2. Leave to appeal was granted on June 29, 2018.</P>
