<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. Appellate jurisprudence<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC><YEAR>1999</YEAR><CITE>)46 O.R. (3d) 330</CITE></CASEREF>, Plaintiff's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;BOA&rdquo;), Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> has confirmed a) that self-represented litigants are not to be awarded costs at all unless the self-represented litigant proves opportunity cost (the Opportunity Costs Rule or &ldquo;OCR&rdquo;);<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and b) that if the self-represented litigant does prove opportunity costs and is allowed costs, the costs awarded are to be nominal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF>, BOA, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Self-represented litigants should not be awarded normal partial indemnity costs.</P>
<P>2. This appeal raises two issues: a) for the purpose of the OCR, what is the nature of the evidence that the self-represented litigant must show in order to prove opportunity cost; and b) whether a self-represented litigant who is also a lawyer should be able to recover costs in the same amount as a successful litigant would have been awarded if they had been represented by a lawyer charging ordinary fees.</P>
<P>3. As will be explained below, it is the appellants' position that a) in order to prove opportunity costs for the purposes of the OCR, self-represented litigants must prove that they incurred an opportunity cost that could not have been avoided had the litigation work been done after normal business hours, and b) self-represented litigants who are lawyers should not be in a privileged position when it comes to costs awards.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<P>4. In September 2015, the appellants/clients (&ldquo;Clients&rdquo;) issued an application in Superior court to assess the fees of the respondents/lawyers (&ldquo;Lawyers&rdquo;), who had billed the Clients fees of over $500,000 in defending their interests in <CASEREF><SOC>DSLC Capital Corporation v. Credifinance Securities Limited, Donabo Inc., Georges Benarroch, Marjorie Ann Glover, and Credifinance Capital Corp.</SOC></CASEREF> with Court File No. 09-CL-8003.</P>
<P>5. On February 7, 2018, the application was heard and dismissed by the Honourable Justice Markus Koehnen (the &ldquo;Costs Judge&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. At the conclusion of the hearing on February 7, after the Court read its reasons dismissing the application, the Lawyers made oral submissions on costs and submitted a costs outline supporting a request for costs in the amount of $60,583.05, which was based on the time the Lawyers spent defending the application calculated at 60% of their standard hourly rate, i.e., the rate that the Lawyers charge the public for their legal services.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Costs Outline of Respondents Fred Tayar &amp; Associates P.C. et al, Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellants (&ldquo;ABC&rdquo;), Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. The Lawyers were self-represented at the application, and thus did not actually incur these costs.</P>
<P>8. In the Lawyers' costs submissions made orally before the Costs Judge, the Lawyers did not argue that they had incurred opportunity costs in the context of defending the application.</P>
<P>9. The Clients sought and received permission from the Costs Judge to respond in writing to the Lawyers' oral submissions.</P>
<P>10. On February 14, 2018, the Clients provided their responding submissions on the subject of costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Responding Costs Submissions of Applicants Georges Benarroch et al, ABC, Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In these submissions, the Clients argued that the Lawyers should receive no costs, as they had not alleged that they had incurred opportunity cost, nor provided evidence as to opportunity cost incurred. The Clients argued in the alternative that the Lawyers should receive costs in an amount not greater than $5,860, including HST, as nominal costs, following the Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Mustang</EM>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>11. In their submissions, the Clients set out the binding jurisprudence on the subject of costs awards to self-represented litigants, which states clearly that the courts may not award costs to the self-represented litigant, even a self-represented lawyer, absent evidence of opportunity cost to the litigant: <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>12. In a reply dated February 26, 2018,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter to Justice Markus Koehnen from Respondent Fred Tayar &amp; Associates P .C., ABC, Tab 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Lawyers acknowledged that <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC></CASEREF> was the binding authority, and alleged for the first time that they had suffered opportunity costs in responding to the application. In support of their submission, the Lawyers provided affidavits with bald assertions on their opportunity costs. They provided no evidence as to the number or nature of the files they claim to have turned away, their estimate as to the income they gave up in doing so, or the fact that they could not have found the time to do them in addition to their self-represented work on this matter. The affidavits contained only vague statements that they performed the work during normal business hours and had to refer files to other lawyers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavits of Fred Tayar and Colby Linthwaite sworn February 26, 2018, ABC, Tabs 9 and 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. In a sur-reply dated March 1, 2018, the Clients identified and explained the following legal errors in the Lawyers' approach: a) costs awarded a self-represented litigant should be nominal, whether the litigant is a lawyer or not; b) to be awarded costs at all, a self-represented litigant must demonstrate opportunity cost; and c) new evidence must not be served by way of reply.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Further Responding Costs submissions of Applicants Georges Benarroch et al, ABC, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. On March 3, 2018, the Costs Judge provided his endorsement in favour of the Lawyers,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Endorsement of Justice Koehnen dated March 3, 2018, ABC, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> awarding them the full amount of costs they requested, calculated at 60% of the fees the Lawyers would charge the public, i.e. full partial indemnity costs.</P>
<P>15. The Clients sought leave to appeal the decision of the Costs Judge. On June 29, 2018 the Clients were granted leave to appeal the decision to the Ontario Court of Appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Endorsement granting Leave to Appeal the Costs Decision, ABC, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>Issues</TI>
<P>16. For the purposes of the opportunity cost that is required by the foundational case of <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Fong</EM>&rdquo;),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>[1999] O.J. No. 4600 (C.A.), BOA, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which sets out the terms under which a self-represented litigant is entitled to claim costs for work performed on litigation:
<P1>(a) Are self-represented litigants entitled to costs if they choose to forego remunerative activity and work on the litigation during normal business hours, but could have performed both the work on the litigation and the remunerative activity, if they had worked on the litigation outside of normal business hours? Said another way, for the purposes of demonstrating opportunity cost as required by Fong, can the self-represented litigant claim for opportunity cost that could have been avoided if the self-represented litigant worked on the litigation at home or on vacation?</P1>
<P1>(b) Should a self-represented litigant, who also happens to be a lawyer, be able to recover costs in exactly the same amount as a successful litigant who is being represented by a lawyer charging legal fees?</P1>
<P1>(c) When is it permissible to serve new evidence by way of reply?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Standard Of Review</TI>
<P>17. The Supreme Court of Canada has held that the standard of review on pure questions of law is one of correctness, and that &ldquo;an appellate court is thus free to replace the opinion of a trial judge with its own.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>[2002] 2 SCR 235</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>, BOA, Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. It is the Clients' position that the Costs Judge erred on the following issues of law in awarding the Lawyers partial indemnity costs for successfully defeating the application:
<P1>(a) The Costs Judge erred in awarding the Respondents opportunity costs without requiring them to demonstrate that the work performed could not have been done on weekends or evenings, contrary to the principle articulated in <CASEREF><SOC>Logtenberg v. ING Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2008 CarswellOnt 2390, BOA, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<EM>Logtenberg</EM>&rdquo;), where the court held that evidence of lost personal time does not amount to an opportunity cost.</P1>
<P1>(b) The Costs Judge erred in holding that the costs awarded a self-represented litigant should be &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;, as opposed to &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;, and specifically in awarding a self-represented litigant partial indemnity costs at exactly the same rate as would be awarded against a losing party who was not self-represented, contrary to the binding decision of the Divisional Court in <EM>Mustang</EM>, and to other jurisprudence which has awarded only very modest costs to self-represented litigants;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Costs Judge erred in permitting evidence of opportunity costs to be introduced by way of Reply, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Friends of Lansdowne v. Ottawa</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2011 ONSC 1015, BOA, Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<EM>Lansdowne</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 56;</P1></P>
<P>19. The Clients seek an order reversing the Cost Judge's decision, awarding zero costs or in the alternative nominal costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Costs For Self-Represented Litigants</TI>
<P>20. In <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>[1999] O.J. No. 4600 (C.A.), BOA, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Sharpe J.A., writing for the Court of Appeal for Ontario, noted that &ldquo;the preponderance of modem authority supports the contention that both self-represented lawyers and self-represented lay litigants may be awarded costs and that such costs may include allowances for counsel fees&rdquo;.</P>
<P>21. However, Justice Sharpe held that:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>[S]elf-represented litigants, be they legally trained or not, are not entitled to costs calculated on the same basis as those of the litigant who retains counsel. As the Chorley case, supra, recognized, all litigants suffer a loss of time through their involvement in the legal process. <BOLD>The self-represented litigant should not recover costs for the time and effort that any litigant would have to devote to the case. Costs should only be awarded to those lay litigants who can demonstrate that they devoted time and effort to do the work ordinarily done by a lawyer retained to conduct the litigation, <UNDER>and that as a result</UNDER>, they incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity</BOLD>. As the early Chancery rule recognized, a self-represented lay litigant should receive only a &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo; allowance for the loss of time devoted to preparing and presenting the case. This excludes routine awards on a per diem basis to litigants who would ordinarily be in attendance at court in any event [emphasis added].</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>22. In <EM>Mustang</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2010 ONSC 3444, BOA, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Divisional Court made clear that the rule in <EM>Fong</EM>, cited above, that an SRL cannot recover any costs absent evidence of opportunity cost, is binding jurisprudence which cannot be deviated from, and no injustice arises from following that rule.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. In <EM>Mustang</EM>, the lower court motions judge was satisfied that the defendant had done work that would ordinarily have been done by a lawyer and he determined that in the particular circumstances of the case this was sufficient to justify an award of costs notwithstanding the absence of proof that an opportunity cost had been incurred.</P>
<P>24. Speaking for the Divisional Court, Jennings. J. stated: <FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>In my opinion, the language used by Sharpe J.A. [in <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC></CASEREF>] is clear. First, to receive costs a lay litigant must demonstrate that he or she devoted time and effort to do the work ordinarily done by a lawyer and that as a result he or she incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity. Second, if an opportunity cost is proved a self-represented litigant should only receive a moderate or reasonable allowance for the loss of time devoted to preparing and presenting the case.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>25. In sum, Jennings J. clearly set out the rule regarding the entitlement of SRLs to costs as follows: &ldquo;<EM>Simply stated, no proof of opportunity cost, no nominal costs available</EM>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>20 <EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added].</P>
<P>26. In the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Sydney Charendoff et al. v. Alec Mclennan and 124155 Canada Inc. et al</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2012 ONSC 7241, BOA, Tab 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<EM>Sydney Charendoff</EM>&rdquo;), MacDonnell J. of the Ontario Superior Court of Justice made it clear that the Divisional Court's holding in <EM>Mustang</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, and the Court of Appeal for Ontario's holding in <EM>Fong</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, extend to self-represented lawyers as well.</P>
<P>27. The Court stated: <FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>The cases I have referred to make it clear that it will not be assumed that an opportunity cost has been incurred. I do not read Fong as taking a different position where the self-represented litigant happens to be a lawyer.</P>
<P>What Fong did is extend the lost opportunity principle, which had been used to justify awarding costs to self-represented lawyers, to all self-represented litigants. <BOLD>In other words, Fong put all self-represented litigants into the same boat in relation to the criteria for an award of costs. It is no more obvious that lawyers who choose to act for themselves will have to forego other remunerative activity than it is for individuals with other employment. Accordingly, if self-represented lawyers wish to obtain costs orders, they must establish that they did in fact suffer the loss of an earnings opportunity</BOLD>. Even if the loss of an earnings opportunity can be assumed in some cases, I would not make such an assumption here. <BOLD>There is no basis upon which it could reasonably be inferred that Mr. McLennan had to decline other remunerative activity in order to work on his own case</BOLD>. .... The rule articulated by Justice Jennings on behalf of the Divisional Court is binding and there is no reason not to apply it in this case [emphasis added].</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>28. Similarly, in <EM>Tiago</EM>, Stinson J. stated:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2012 ONSC 5090 at para. 6, BOA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>[I]n Ontario, a judge may exercise his or her discretion to award costs to a self-represented litigant only if (1) the litigant devoted time and effort to do the work ordinarily done by a lawyer; and (2) that as a result she or he incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity...</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>To meet the second part of the test, a self-represented litigant must prove that he or she gave up remunerative activity</BOLD>... [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. Stinson J. ultimately held that he was unable to award costs due to the plaintiffs' failure to provide evidence or proof supporting their claim for lost opportunity costs: <FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>In light of the plaintiffs' failure to provide evidence or proof supporting their claim for lost opportunity costs, I am unable to award the nominal costs otherwise provided for under the legal authority binding on me in Ontario</BOLD>. I therefore award no costs to the plaintiffs in respect of their personal time devoted to the litigation [emphasis added].</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>What Are Opportunity Costs?</TI>
<P>30. In <EM>Logtenberg</EM>, Gauthier J. noted at para. 35 that &ldquo;there is no authority to award costs or time taken away from family or for reduced quality of life, as claimed by the plaintiff&rdquo;. Self-represented litigants have always given up their time and contributed their efforts to their own cause. These sacrifices may well infringe on the litigant's quality of life, whether the litigant in question is a neurosurgeon, an investment banker, or an unemployed person. Gauthier J. states clearly that this does not give rise to an award of costs.</P>
<P>31. In contrast, the Costs Judge in the present case took a diametrically opposed position when it came to finding opportunity costs in the case of lawyers representing themselves without proof or allegation that the opportunity costs complained of could not have been accomplished had the Lawyers taken away from home or vacation time to work on the application. He indicated, at para. 10 of his endorsement, that &ldquo;forcing the lawyer to demonstrate that he or she could not have worked on weekends or into the evenings is the beginning of a never ending forensic inquiry&rdquo;. He then went on to say that &ldquo;the next step would no doubt be to ask why the lawyer could not have worked later into the evening or longer on weekends or worked on vacations in order to address the applicants' proceeding&rdquo;.</P>
<P>32. The Cost Judge's approach essentially allows the Lawyers to claim for missing home or family time contrary to <EM>Logtenberg</EM>. In so doing, the Costs Judge fell into legal error, which this appeal seeks to correct.</P>
<P>33. However, even if the Court were to accept that the Lawyers did incur opportunity costs, which is denied, the Cost Judge's award of $60,583.05 amounts to normal partial indemnity costs and is excessive, and incorrect at law.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Costs Awarded A Self-Represented Litigant Should Be Nominal</TI>
<P>34. In <EM>Mustang</EM>, at para. 23, Jennings J. held for a unanimous Divisional Court panel that to receive costs, a self-represented litigant must provide evidence that he or she incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity. At para. 27 she succinctly summarized the standard at which costs should be assessed: &ldquo;Simply stated, no proof of opportunity costs, no <EM>nominal</EM> costs available&rdquo; (emphasis added).</P>
<P>35. In contrast, the Costs Judge in the present case held at para. 12 that the Lawyers' rates of $300 per hour and higher was &ldquo;<EM>moderate and reasonable</EM>,&rdquo; when the standard clearly articulated in <EM>Mustang</EM> is that of <EM>nominal</EM> costs.</P>
<P>36. In <CASEREF><SOC>H. (D.) v. Hydro One Networks Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>[2002] O.J. No. 4547, BOA, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> at para 33, Master Dash held that he was prepared to award the self-represented litigant costs at the rate of $60 per hour, which is the maximum rate under the costs grid payable to a student-at-law on a partial indemnity scale. In <CASEREF><SOC>White v. Ritchie</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>[2009] O.J. No. 2360, BOA, Tab 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> at para 24, Newbould J. awarded a self-represented party an allowance of $15,000 in total for the work done, and in <CASEREF><SOC>Henderson v. Pearlman</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2010 ONSC 149 at para. 4, BOA, Tab 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Hennessy J. awarded the self-represented litigant 120 hours of time spent at $20 per hour.</P>
<P>37. This level of modest costs award has been determined to be appropriate for self-represented parties who have not incurred actual legal fees in pursuing or defending their case. Thus, in <EM>Sydney Charendoff</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2012 ONSC 7241, BOA, Tab 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> at para 18, McDonnell J. determined that &ldquo;the claim for compensation at an hourly rate of $375 is unjustifiable.&rdquo; The overarching principal with respect to costs is that of indemnity: see Rule 57.01(1)(0.a). It is clear that unless costs are actually incurred out of pocket or some other extraordinary situation prevails, the rule with respect to litigants representing themselves is that nominal to modest costs are all that the courts should award.</P>
<P>38. In light of the above cases, the decision to award costs in the amount of $60,583.05 to a self-represented litigant, at hourly rates ranging from $300 to $350 per hour, amounts to an error of law.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>New Evidence Must Not Be Served By Way Of Reply</TI>
<P>39. The Costs Judge further fell into error when he admitted the Lawyers' affidavits by way of reply.</P>
<P>40. In <CASEREF><SOC>Lockridge v. Director, Ministry of the Environment</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2013 ONSC 6935. BOA, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<EM>Lockridge</EM>&rdquo;), this court set out five factors to determine whether new evidence should be permitted by way of reply:
<QUOTE><P>The court will consider the potential prejudice and unfair surprise to the respondents; whether the evidence is responsive to the respondents' case or is merely confirmatory; whether the evidence will assist the court in making its determination on the merits; whether the evidence was available and/or could not have been anticipated as being relevant at the time the application was filed; and the applicants' reasons for their delay in adducing the evidence&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>41. Under this framework, the Lawyers should not have been permitted to serve new evidence by way of reply. There was significant prejudice and unfair surprise in permitting them to do so after the Clients had already advised in their submissions as to what the relevant law was; the evidence is vague and self-serving and thus cannot be of any assistance to the Court; that such evidence would be relevant could certainly have been anticipated at the outset of costs submissions; and there is no good reason for the Lawyers having delayed in adducing the evidence.</P>
<P>42. In addition to the above, providing affidavit evidence by way of reply enabled the Lawyers to come up with a statement vague enough not to be examined carefully, but that nonetheless managed to address the exact issues raised by the Clients in their submissions. This is precisely what the jurisprudence on serving new evidence by way of reply is designed to prevent.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>43. The Clients respectfully submit their appeal of the order of the Costs Judge be allowed and the order of the Costs Judge substituted with an award of no costs, or in the alternative, the sum of $5,000 representing nominal costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</P>
<P>&ellip35; Eli Karp/Jennie Brodski</P>
<P>Morganti &amp; Co, P.C.</P></BLOCK1>
