<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF MOTION FOR LEAVE TO APPEAL COSTS DECISION (Costs Decision of Justice Markus Koehnen dated March 3, 2018)</TI>
<P>TAKE NOTICE THAT the Plaintiff, Georges Benarroch (the &ldquo;Moving Party&rdquo;) will make a motion to the Court on a date to be fixed by the Registrar, at the Courthouse at 180 Queen Street West, Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P><BOLD>METHOD OF HEARING</BOLD>: The motion is to be heard in writing.</P>
<P>THE RELIEF SOUGHT:</P>
<P>1. An Order granting leave to the Moving Parties to appeal the costs award granted by the application judge.</P>
<P>2. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THE MOTION ARE:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. The Respondents were awarded costs of $60,583.05 arising from a failed application to assess the fees of the Respondents.</P>
<P>2. The Application Judge erred in law in holding that the costs awarded a self-represented litigant should be &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;, as opposed to &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;, contrary to the binding decision of the Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF>;</P>
<P>3. The Application Judge further erred in law in permitting evidence of opportunity costs to be introduced by way of Reply, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Friends of Lansdowne v. Ottawa</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 1015</CITE><PARANUM>56</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>4. The Application Judge further erred in law in awarding a self-represented litigant partial indemnity costs at exactly the same rate as would be awarded against a losing party who was not self-represented, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC><CITE>[1999] O.J. No. 4600</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>5. The Application Judge further erred in awarding the Respondent opportunity costs without requiring him to demonstrate that the work performed could not have been done on weekends or evenings, contrary to the principle articulated in <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE></CASEREF>, where the court held that evidence of lost personal time does not amount to an opportunity cost.</P>
<P>6. The Application Judge's findings conflict with binding appellate jurisprudence and it is desirable that leave to appeal be granted because the issue of the scale of recovery for costs for self-represented litigants is important and transcends the issues of the parties and relates to issues of the practice of law generally.</P>
<P>7. There is good reason to doubt the correctness of the Order in respect of costs, and the issues raised are of such importance to that leave should be granted. The issues sought to be appealed transcend the issues of the parties and relates to issues of the practice of law generally.</P>
<P>8. S. 133(b) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, Rule 62.02(4)(a),(b) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>;</P>
<P>9. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE FOLLOWING DOCUMENTARY EVIDENCE</BOLD> will be relied on at the hearing of the motion:</P>
<P>1. Endorsement of Justice Koehnen dated March 3, 2018.</P>
<P>2. The Affidavit Evidence of the Respondents dated February 26, 2018;</P>
