<P><EM>Lawyers for the Plaintiff</EM></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;NATURE OF THE MOTION</TI>
<P>1. The Applicants seek leave to appeal the costs order of the Honourable Justice Markus Koehnen (the &ldquo;Costs Judge&rdquo;) dated March 3, 2018, allowing the Respondents' costs in the amount of $60,583.05 including HST and disbursements. The Applicants had brought an application to assess the Respondents' fees. The costs in issue were awarded to the Respondents for successfully resisting the Applicants' assessment application.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>2. Appellate jurisprudence has confirmed that self-represented litigants are not to be awarded costs in amounts nearing what would be awarded had they retained counsel. The costs are to be nominal.</P>
<P>3. The question raised in this motion for leave to appeal is whether a self-represented litigant, who also happens to be a lawyer, should be able to recover costs in the <UNDER>same amount</UNDER> as a successful litigant would have been awarded if they had been represented by a lawyer charging ordinary fees. It is the Applicants' position that appellate jurisprudence confirms that lawyers as personal litigants should be placed in no better position than other self-represented litigants.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<P>4. At the hearing of the application for assessment of the Respondents' fees, the Respondents provided a costs outline, calculated at 60% of their standard hourly rate, i.e., the rate that the Respondents charge the public for their legal services.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Costs Outline of Respondents Fred Tayar &amp; Associates P.C. et al, Motion Record of the Applicants (&ldquo;MRA&rdquo;), Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This roughly corresponds with the rate at which costs are awarded on the standard partial indemnity scale. The Respondents were self-represented at the application, and thus did not actually incur these costs. In the Respondents' costs submissions made orally before the Costs Judge, the Respondents did not argue that they had incurred opportunity costs, nor did they make any attempt to explain why they should receive an award of costs on an equal level to someone who had actually retained counsel.</P>
<P>5. On February 14, 2018, the Applicants provided their responding submissions on the subject of costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Responding Costs Submissions of Applicants Georges Benarroch et al, MRA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In these submissions, the Applicants set out the binding jurisprudence on the subject of costs awards to self-represented litigants, which states clearly that the courts may not award costs to the self-represented litigant, even a self-represented lawyer, absent evidence of opportunity cost to the litigant: <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v. Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>6. In a reply dated February 26, 2018,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter to Justice Markus Koehnen from Respondent Fred Tayar &amp; Associates P.C., MRS, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Respondents provided affidavits containing vague statements wherein they claim that they performed the work for this matter during normal business hours and that they had to refer prospective clients to other lawyers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavits of Fred Tayar and Colby Linthwaite sworn February 26, 2018, MRA, Tabs 4 and 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They provided no evidence as to the number or nature of these files, their estimate as to the income they gave up in turning them away, or the fact that they could not have found the time to do them in addition to their self-represented work on this matter.</P>
<P>7. In a sur-reply dated March 1, 2018, the Applicants detailed the legal errors in the Respondents' approach.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Further Responding Costs submissions of Applicants Georges Benarroch et al, MRA, Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. On March 3, 2018, the Costs Judge provided his endorsement in favour of the Respondents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Endorsement of Justice Koehnen dated March 3, 2018, MRA, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In awarding the self-represented Respondents the same level of costs he would have awarded them had they retained outside counsel, the Costs Judge ignored the governing points of principle articulated by the Court of Appeal and the Supreme Court of Canada. The Costs Judge's ruling likewise directly contradicted existing Divisional Court and Superior Court authority.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>9. Did the Costs Judge err in awarding the Respondents partial indemnity costs? It is the Applicants' position that he erred on three counts, as follows:
<P1>(a) The Costs Judge erred in holding that the costs awarded a self-represented litigant should be &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;, as opposed to &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;, and specifically in awarding a self-represented litigant partial indemnity costs at exactly the same rate as would be awarded against a losing party who was not self-represented, contrary to the binding decision of the Divisional Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 3444</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Mustang</EM>&rdquo;) and to other jurisprudence which has awarded only very modest costs to self-represented litigants;</P1>
<P1>(b) The Costs Judge erred in awarding the Respondents opportunity costs without requiring them to demonstrate that the work performed could not have been done on weekends or evenings, contrary to the principle articulated in <CASEREF><SOC>Logtenberg v. ING Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 2044</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Logtenberg</EM>&rdquo;), where the court held that evidence of lost personal time does not amount to an opportunity cost.</P1>
<P1>(c) The Costs Judge erred in permitting evidence of opportunity costs to be introduced by way of Reply, contrary to <CASEREF><SOC>Friends of Lansdowne v. Ottawa</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 1015</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Lansdowne</EM>&rdquo;) at para. 56;</P1></P>
<P>10. These errors of law demonstrate that leave to appeal ought to be granted, as will be elaborated below.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Rule 62.02(4) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM></TI>
<P>11. S. 62.02(4) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, provides the standard for granting leave to appeal, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Leave to appeal shall not be granted unless,</P>
<P>(a) There is a conflicting decision by another judge or court in Ontario or elsewhere on the matter involved in the proposed appeal and it is, in the opinion of the panel hearing the motion, desirable that leave to appeal be granted; or</P>
<P>(b) There appears to the panel hearing the motion good reason to doubt the correctness of the order in question and the proposed appeal involves matters of such importance that, in the panel's opinion, leave to appeal should be granted.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. While it is only necessary to meet the standards set out in either (a) or (b) above in order for the Court to grant leave to appeal, the present case meets both of them.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Rule 62.02(4)(a)</TI>
<P>13. In <EM>Mustang</EM>, at para. 23, Jennings J. held for a unanimous Divisional Court panel that to receive costs, a self-represented litigant must provide evidence that he or she incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity. At para. 27 she succinctly summarized the standard at which costs should be assessed: &ldquo;Simply stated, no proof of opportunity costs, no <EM>nominal</EM> costs available&rdquo; (emphasis added).</P>
<P>14. By contrast, the Cost Judge in the present case held at para. 12 that the Respondents' rates of $300 per hour and higher was &ldquo;moderate and reasonable,&rdquo; when the standard clearly articulated in <EM>Mustang</EM> is that of <EM>nominal</EM> costs.</P>
<P>15. In addition, in <EM>Logtenberg</EM>, Gauthier J. noted at para. 35 that &ldquo;there is no authority to award costs or time taken away from family or for reduced quality of life, as claimed by the plaintiff&rdquo;. Self-represented litigants have always given up their time and contributed their efforts to their own cause. These sacrifices may well infringe on the litigant's quality of life, whether the litigant in question is a neurosurgeon, an investment banker, or an unemployed person. Gauthier J. states clearly that this does not give rise to an award of costs.</P>
<P>16. By contrast, the Cost Judge in the present case took a diametrically opposed position when it came to lawyers representing themselves. He indicated, at para. 10 of his endorsement, that &ldquo;forcing the lawyer to demonstrate that he or she could not have worked on weekends or into the evenings is the beginning of a never ending forensic inquiry&rdquo;. He then went on to say that &ldquo;the next step would no doubt be to ask why the lawyer could not have worked later into the evening or longer on weekends or worked on vacations in order to address the applicants' proceeding&rdquo;.</P>
<P>17. This approach of valuing a lawyer's time without the need for any particular inquiry places lawyers in a preferred position over and above all other personal litigants. The Court of Appeal has specifically admonished that lawyers are not in a special position when it comes to seeking their own costs as litigants. As Sharpe J.A. put it in <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC><YEAR>1999</YEAR><CITE>46 O.R. (3d) 330</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>, &ldquo;self-represented litigants, <EM>be they legally trained or not</EM>, are not entitled to costs calculated on the same basis as those of the litigant who retains counsel&rdquo; (emphasis added).</P>
<P>18. Accordingly, the Cost Judge's ruling is at odds with the statement of general principle by the Court of Appeal, and is directly contrary to the general rule as set out in <EM>Mustang</EM> and <EM>Logtenberg</EM>.</P>
<P>19. As a matter of legal coherence, it is desirable for leave to appeal to be granted where there are conflicting judgments of the lower courts. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mask v. Silvercorp Metals, Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 4647</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Mask</EM>&rdquo;), the court expounded on this policy at para. 9, as follows:
<QUOTE><P>If leave to appeal is to be granted on the grounds of conflicting decisions, the court must be satisfied [...] that it is desirable that leave to appeal be granted having regard to such factors as what is at stake in the order being challenged, the likelihood of the appeal being successful, the sufficiency of the record for the purposes of deciding the issues on appeal, and the problems of expense and delay.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>20. At stake in this case is not only the scale of cost recovery for the self-represented litigant, but the permissibility of inflating that recovery by serving new evidence by way of reply. This combination of substantive and procedural issues encompasses matters that transcend the issues of the parties and relate to the practice of law generally.</P>
<P>21. As specified at para 56 of <EM>Landsdowne</EM>, &ldquo;reply evidence should be limited to proper reply. That is, it should respond to evidence raised by the other party and should not be evidence that ought to have been submitted in the first place.&rdquo; Providing affidavit evidence by way of reply enabled the Respondents to come up with a statement vague enough not to be examined carefully, but that nonetheless managed to address the exact issues raised by the Appellants in their submissions. This is precisely what the jurisprudence on serving new evidence by way of reply is designed to prevent.</P>
<P>22. It seems likely that the appeal will be successful in light of the fact that there are well reasoned decisions by the Superior Court, Divisional Court, and Court of Appeal that conflict with key points in the Cost Judge's endorsement. Moreover, it is likely that the appeal will succeed in light of the fact that the Cost Judge relied on new evidence provided by way of reply, which should not have been permitted.</P>
<P>23. The documentary record for the purposes of deciding the issues on appeal is complete, and consists only of the endorsement of the Costs Judge and the affidavit evidence of the Respondents on their reply cost submissions. Given that this is the final step in this proceeding and that the Respondents will most likely be representing themselves, there is no problem of either expense or delay.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Rule 62.02(4)(b)</TI>
<P>24. In <EM>Mask</EM>, at para. 11, the court observed that &ldquo;in order to show that there is good reason to doubt the correctness of the order, the moving party need not show that the order is wrong or probably wrong, but rather, that the soundness of the order is open to very serious debate&rdquo;.</P>
<P>25. In <CASEREF><SOC>H. (D.) v. Hydro One Networks Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No. 4547</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Master Dash held that he was prepared to award the self-represented litigant costs at the rate of $60 per hour, which is the maximum rate under the costs grid payable to a student-at-law on a partial indemnity scale. In <CASEREF><SOC>White v. Ritchie</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 2360</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Newbould J. awarded a self-represented party &ldquo;a reasonable allowance for the work done&rdquo; of $15,000 in total, and in <CASEREF><SOC>Henderson v. Pearlman</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 149</CITE></CASEREF>, Hennessy J. awarded the self-represented litigant 120 hours of time spent at $20 per hour.</P>
<P>26. This level of modest costs award has been determined to be appropriate for self-represented parties who have not incurred actual legal fees in pursuing or defending their case. Thus, in <CASEREF><SOC>Sydney Charendoff et al v. Alec McLennan and 124155 Ontario Inc. et al</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 7241</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Sydney Charendoff</EM>&rdquo;), McDonnell J. determined that &ldquo;the claim for compensation at an hourly rate of $375 is unjustifiable.&rdquo; The overarching principal with respect to costs is that of indemnity: see Rule 57.01(1)(j). It is clear that unless costs are actually incurred out of pocket or some other extraordinary situation prevails, the rule with respect to litigants representing themselves is that nominal to modest costs are all that the courts should award.</P>
<P>27. In light of the above cases, the decision to award costs in the amount of $60,583.05 to a self-represented litigant, at hourly rates ranging from $300 to $350 per hour, is indeed open to very serious debate.</P>
<P>28. In <EM>Mask</EM>, the court further noted that in order to show that a matter is of general importance, &ldquo;the moving party must show that the matter is of importance to the public or to the development of the law or to the administration of justice and that ... [it] transcends the importance of the matter to the particular parties&rdquo;.</P>
<P>29. The question of whether a self-represented litigant, who happens to also be a lawyer, should be in a privileged position when it comes to recovering costs raises a serious question of public policy. It also implicates an important access to justice issue insofar as it operates to the detriment of all non-lawyer self-represented litigants.</P>
<P>30. In <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia (Minister of Forests) v. Okanagan Indian Band</SOC><CITE>[2003] 3 S.C.R. 371</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada made it clear that access to justice is of great relevance to costs awards. As McLachlin C J. put it, at para. 28, quoting <CASEREF><SOC>Rogers v. Sudbury (Administrator of Ontario Works)</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>57 O.R. (3d) 467</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF>, &ldquo;costs can be used as an instrument of policy&rdquo;. In this respect, the court should strive to fashion costs awards on as egalitarian a basis as possible.</P>
<P>31. The circumstances of &ldquo;ordinary citizens&rdquo; in using the courts are &ldquo;recognized as a legitimate and important policy objective&rdquo;: <EM>Okanagan Indian Band</EM>, supra, at para. 28. By contrast, access to justice is not served by privileging lawyer litigants as did the Costs Judge.</P>
<P>32. Accordingly, the question raised in this application is of great importance to the public. Leave to appeal should be granted so that the Court of Appeal can rationalize the conflicting case law and bring the ruling into line with the overarching principles that govern all costs awards.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>31. The Applicants respectfully submit that leave to appeal the order of the Costs Judge be granted.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Eli Karp/Jennie M. Brodski</P></BLOCK1>
