<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDING PARTY RESPONDENTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The respondents do not accept the statements of fact made in paragraphs 4&ndash;8 of the applicants' factum, as those paragraphs are suffused with argument. The respondents' summary of the relevant facts is as follows.</P>
<P>2. This is a motion for leave to appeal a costs award.</P>
<P>3. The applicants brought an application for an order directing an assessment of accounts rendered by the respondent law firm, respecting work performed by the respondent lawyers. The application was dismissed by Justice Koehnen of the Superior Court of Justice (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Application Judge</BOLD>&rdquo;), in reasons dated February 7, 2018.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons of the Honourable Justice Koehnen dated February 7, 2018, Tab 1 to the Responding Motion Record of the Respondents (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Respondents' Record</BOLD>&rdquo;) at Tab 2; Order of the Honourable Justice Koehnen dated February 7, 2018, Respondents' Record at Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No appeal was taken from that decision.</P>
<P>4. At the conclusion of the hearing of the application, the Application Judge invited oral submissions on costs. The respondents sought costs of $60,583.05 on a partial indemnity basis, including disbursements and HST. The applicants were not prepared to argue costs, and asked for the opportunity to make written submissions, which the Application Judge granted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Endorsement of the Honourable Justice Koehnen dated March 3, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Reasons</BOLD>&rdquo;) at paragraphs 2-3, Motion Record of the Applicants (&ldquo;<BOLD>Applicants' Record</BOLD>&rdquo;) at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>5. In their written submissions, the applicants argued that the respondents should not be entitled to costs because they had represented themselves, and had provided no evidence of lost opportunity costs associated with that self-representation. The applicants submitted that lawyers who act for themselves can only recover costs if they can demonstrate that they have been taken away from otherwise remunerative work in order to represent themselves. Even then, the applicants stated that any recovery should be &ldquo;nominal&rdquo; and there should be no recovery for any time that a litigant would ordinarily be required to spend in the course of litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 4, Applicants' Record at Tab 8; Responding Costs Submissions of the Applicants, Applicants' Record at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>6. The Application Judge asked the respondents for their submissions concerning lost opportunity costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from the Honourable Justice Koehnen to Fred Tayar, Peter Askew and Eli Karp dated February 21, 2018, Respondents' Record at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. The respondents replied and included affidavits of the individual respondents attesting to the fact that, had they not been required to spend time responding to the application, they would have spent the time on remunerative client work, and that they had turned away work as a result of this litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 5, Applicants' Record at Tab 8; Affidavit of Fred Tayar affirmed February 26, 2018 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Tayar Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;) at paragraphs 2&ndash;4, Applicants' Record at Tab 5; Affidavit of Colby Linthwaite affirmed February 26, 2018 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Linthwaite Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;) at paragraphs 2-3, Applicants' Record at Tab 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. The applicants chose not to cross-examine on the affidavits.</P>
<P>9. Instead, the applicants filed sur-reply in which they submitted that the respondents' affidavits did not provide sufficient detail concerning the prospective clients on whose files they could have worked, how much income they would have earned from those files, and the lawyers to whom those files were referred. The applicants also submitted that the respondents could have worked on weekends or in the evening to respond to the application.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 6, Applicants' Record at Tab 8; Further Responding Costs Submissions of the Applicants, Applicants' Record at Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. Having considered the submissions of the parties, the Application Judge awarded the respondents costs of $60,583.05, including disbursements and HST.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 21, Applicants' Record at Tab 8; Order of the Honourable Justice Koehnen dated February 7, 2018, Respondents' Record at Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is the award at issue.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;POSITION OF THE RESPONDENTS WITH RESPECT TO THE ISSUES RAISED BY THE APPLICANTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Issue One: the Test for the Granting of Leave to Appeal</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Applicants Have Not Set Out the Correct Test</EM></TI>
<P>11. In paragraphs 11 and 12 of their factum, the applicants state that the applicable standard for the granting of leave to appeal is set out in Rule 62.02(4) the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notice of Motion, paragraph 19, Tab 1 in the Motion Record</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is not accurate. This Court has held that the test for leave to appeal a costs award is as follows.
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Test for Leave to Appeal</EM></TI>
<P><EM>23 Appeals in which the sole issue is costs [lie] only with leave of the court: see Courts of Justice Act, R.S.O. 1990, c. C-43, s. 133(b)</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>24 In</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Brad-Jay Investments Ltd. v. Szijjarto</SOC><CITE>[2006] O.J. No. 5078</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>at para. 21, this court said:</EM>
<QUOTE><P><EM>Leave to appeal a costs order will not be granted save in obvious cases where the party seeking leave convinces the court that there are &ldquo;strong grounds upon which the appellate court could find that the judge erred in exercising his discretion&rdquo;</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><EM>25 This court has also said that &ldquo;[l]eave to appeal a costs order, standing alone, is granted only sparingly.&rdquo; See</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Inter-Trust Mortgage Investment Corp. v. Robinson</SOC><CITE>1999 CarswellOnt 1733</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>at para. 12</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>26 As to the grounds upon which an appellate court should set aside a costs order, Arbour J. said in</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Open Window Bakery Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>2003</YEAR><CITE>[2004] 1 S.C.R. 303</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>at para. 27:</EM>
<QUOTE><P><EM>A court should set aside a costs award on appeal only if the trial judge has made an error in principle or if the costs award is plainly wrong</EM> (<CASEREF><SOC>Duong v. NN Life Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>141 O.A.C. 307</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><EM>27 I am also mindful that a costs award is a discretionary order and that the judge of first instance is in the best position to determine the entitlement, scale and quantum of any such award</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McNaughton Automotive Ltd. v. Co-operators General Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2008 ONCA 597</CITE><PARANUM>23&ndash;27</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondents' Book of Authorities (&ldquo;<BOLD>Respondents' Authorities</BOLD>&rdquo;) at Tab 1; see also <CASEREF><SOC>Feinstein v Freedman</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 205</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM></CASEREF>, Respondents' Authorities at Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. Thus, to succeed the applicants must demonstrate that it is &ldquo;obvious&rdquo; that there are &ldquo;strong grounds&rdquo; upon which this Court could find that the Application Judge erred in exercising his discretion. Stated differently, the applicants have the burden of showing that this is one of the rare cases in which a Court exercising deference to the judge of first instance could find that he was &ldquo;plainly wrong&rdquo;. The applicants cannot discharge this burden.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Issue Two: The Granting of Costs to a Self-Represented Lawyer</EM></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Law</EM></TI>
<P>13. The applicants have ignored both the letter and the spirit of the binding case, which is this Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Fong v. Chan</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>(1999) 46 O.R. (3d) 330 (CA), Book of Authorities of the Applicants (&ldquo;<BOLD>Applicants' Authorities</BOLD>&rdquo;) at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Fong</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;). In that decision, Justice Sharpe carefully reviewed the jurisprudence concerning the granting of costs to self-represented lawyers, and concluded as follows.
<QUOTE><P><EM>21 It is apparent from this review of the case law that the preponderance of modern authority supports the contention that both self-represented lawyers and self-represented lay litigants may be awarded costs and that such costs may include allowances for counsel fees. [...]</EM></P>
<P><EM>22 Quite apart from authority and as a matter of principle, it seems to me to be difficult to justify a categorical rule denying recovery of costs by self-represented litigants. As noted in Fellowes McNeil, supra and in Skidmore, supra, modern cost rules are designed to foster three fundamental purposes: (1) to indemnify successful litigants for the cost of litigation; (2) to encourage settlements; and (3) to discourage and sanction inappropriate behaviour by litigants. It seems to me that all three purposes are fostered by allowing the trial judge a discretion to award costs to self-represented litigants</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>[...]</EM></P>
<P><EM>24 A rule precluding recovery of costs, in whole or in part, by self-represented litigants would deprive the court of a potentially useful tool to encourage settlements and to discourage or sanction inappropriate behaviour. For example, an opposite party should not be able to ignore the reasonable settlement offer of a self-represented litigant with impunity from the usual costs consequences. Nor, in my view, is it desirable to immunize such a party from costs awards designed to sanction inappropriate behaviour simply because the other party is a self-represented litigant</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>25 I would add that nothing in these reasons is meant to suggest that a self-represented litigant has an automatic right to recover costs. The matter remains fully within the discretion of the trial judge, and as Ellen Macdonald J. observed in Fellows</EM>, <CASEREF><SOC>McNeil v. Kansa</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra, there are undoubtedly cases where it is inappropriate for a lawyer to appear in person, and there will be cases where the self-represented litigant's conduct of the proceedings is inappropriate. The trial judge maintains a discretion to make the appropriate costs award, including denial of costs</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>26 I would also add that self-represented litigants, be they legally trained or not, are not entitled to costs calculated on the same basis as those of the litigant who retains counsel. As the Chorley case, supra, recognized, all litigants suffer a loss of time through their involvement in the legal process. The self-represented litigant should not recover costs for the time and effort that any litigant would have to devote to the case. Costs should only be awarded to those lay litigants who can demonstrate that they devoted time and effort to do the work ordinarily done by a lawyer retained to conduct the litigation, and that as a result, they incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity. As the early Chancery rule recognized, a self-represented lay litigant should receive only a &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or&rdquo; reasonable&rdquo; allowance for the loss of time devoted to preparing and presenting the case. This excludes routine awards on a per diem basis to litigants who would ordinarily be in attendance at court in any event. The trial judge is particularly well-placed to assess the appropriate allowance, if any, for a self-represented litigant, and accordingly, the trial judge should either fix the costs when making such an award or provide clear guidelines to the Assessment Officer as to the manner in which the costs are to be assessed</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>14. This is the law of Ontario, and it emphasizes the discretion of the trial judge. Justice Sharpe cites this discretion, explicitly or implicitly, five times in the above passage, summarized by his holding that &ldquo;<EM>[t]he trial judge is particularly well-placed to assess the appropriate allowance</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> His Honour limits the trial judge's discretion in only two ways.</P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>Loss of Opportunity</EM></TI>
<P>15. Firstly, the self-represented lawyer must demonstrate to the satisfaction of the trial judge that he incurred an opportunity cost by foregoing remunerative activity in favour of the litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Application Judge held that the respondents had met this requirement, as they had filed affidavits &ldquo;<EM>attesting to the fact that, had they not been required to spend time responding to this application, they would have spent the time on remunerative client work</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraphs 7-8, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The applicants do not challenge this finding. Instead, they allege error in findings that do not exist.</P>
<P>16. In paragraphs 15 and 16 of their factum, the applicants incorrectly suggest that the respondents have been awarded costs for time taken away from family or for reduced quality of life. The respondents made no such claim, and were given no such award. Each of the affidavits affirmed that the time spent on the application had been spent during normal business hours.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tayar Affidavit at paragraph 2, Applicants' Record at Tab 5; Linthwaite Affidavit at paragraph 2, Applicants' Record at Tab 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Application Judge's holding concerning work on weekends<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 10, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (quoted in the applicants' paragraph 16) was in response to a different argument made by the applicants, being that the individual respondents <EM>should have</EM> spent weekends responding to the application, rather than working hours, as this would have allowed the applicants to claim that the respondents were not entitled to any costs whatsoever.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Further Responding Costs Submissions of the Applicants, at paragraphs 6 and 8, Applicants' Record at Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (There is, of course, no jurisprudential support for this posited obligation to spend personal time on lawsuits.)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Neither of the cases cited by the applicants on this point, being <CASEREF><SOC>Tiago v Meisels</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 5090</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Logenberg v ING Insurance Co.</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>167 A.C.W.S. (3d) 655</CITE></CASEREF>, says anything of the sort. <EM>Tiago</EM> holds that costs cannot be awarded for personal time in the absence of evidence of lost opportunity costs (at paragraph 9). <EM>Logenberg</EM> holds that &ldquo;there is no authority to award costs for time taken away from family, or for a reduced quality of life, as claimed by the Plaintiff&rdquo; (at paragraph 35).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. In paragraph 17 of their factum, the applicants assert that the Application Judge's &ldquo;<EM>approach of valuing a lawyer's time without the need for any particular inquiry places lawyers in a preferred position over and above all other personal litigants</EM>.&rdquo; This &ldquo;<EM>preferred position</EM>&rdquo; argument is later relied upon to suggest that this application raises &ldquo;<EM>a serious question of public policy</EM>&rdquo;, and an &ldquo;<EM>important access to justice issue</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum, at paragraphs 29&ndash;31</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The applicants are again badly misrepresenting the decision made.</P>
<P>18. The applicants were served with affidavits. If they wanted a &ldquo;<EM>particular inquiry</EM>&rdquo; into the matters affirmed to therein, it was <EM>their responsibility</EM> to perform that inquiry. They chose not to cross-examine, and thereby left that evidence unchallenged. Sending sur-reply to the Application Judge in which they complained about details not included in the affidavits did not invest that Judge with the responsibility to inquire for them, nor did it make those complaints reasonable. There is no jurisprudential support for the idea that in order to establish lost opportunity costs, a self-represented lawyer must, (as was demanded by the applicants) produce month-by-month breakdowns of his income, describe &ldquo;the nature of the prospective files&rdquo;, identify the lawyers to whom the files were referred, or estimate &ldquo;how much income [the respondents] may have earned&rdquo; from foregone files.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Further Responding Costs Submissions of the Applicants, at paragraphs 5 and 7, Applicants' Record at Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Accordingly:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[9] The level of detailed information the applicant seek from the respondents about the lost opportunities would begin to infringe on solicitor client privilege. The level of inquiry that the applicant[s] seek to make into the daily affairs of the respondents is, in my view, unreasonable. If lawyers engaged in the full-time practice of law swear affidavits indicating that they have turned away work because of this application and have not been cross-examined [about those] affidavits I am entitled to take them at face value</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 9, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. There is no error here.</P>
<P>20. The applicants' complaint about the delivery of the affidavits in reply is another attempt to avoid the consequences of their choice not to cross-examine.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum at paragraphs 9(c) and 21</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Application Judge asked for submissions from the respondents concerning the issue of opportunity costs. The applicants have never suggested that he exceeded his jurisdiction in doing so. The respondents provided those submissions, in the form of the affidavits. The applicants now object that &ldquo;<EM>[p]roviding affidavit evidence by way of reply enabled the Respondents to come up with a statement vague enough not to be examined carefully, but that nonetheless managed to address the exact issues raised by the Applicants in their submissions</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum at paragraph 21</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Again, if the applicants had wanted the affidavits &ldquo;<EM>to be examined carefull</EM>&rdquo;, they could have examined the deponents under oath.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notably, in the case the applicants rely upon for their argument concerning reply evidence, <CASEREF><SOC>Friends of Lansdowne v Ottawa</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 1015</CITE></CASEREF>, the &ldquo;reply&rdquo; affidavits were not struck, (at paragraphs 56 and 60-61) and the Court held that &ldquo;[a]ny unfairness to the respondent can be addressed by permitting a &ldquo;sur-reply&rdquo; (at paragraph 58). The applicants in this matter delivered a sur-reply.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>A Reasonable Allowance</EM></TI>
<P>21. The second limitation on the trial judge's discretion established by <EM>Fong</EM> is as follows. Justice Sharpe, citing earlier English jurisprudence, directed that a self-represented lay litigant should receive a &ldquo;<EM>moderate</EM>&rdquo; or&rdquo; <EM>reasonable</EM>&rdquo; allowance for the loss of time devoted to preparing and presenting the case. He held that <EM>&ldquo;[t]his excludes routine awards on a per diem basis to litigants who would ordinarily be in attendance at court in any event&rdquo;</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Beyond ruling out <EM>per diems</EM>, Justice Sharpe did not define &ldquo;reasonableness&rdquo; in this passage.</P>
<P>22. The respondents submit that Justice Sharpe's larger analysis means that the reasonableness of a costs award is to be measured against His Honour's &ldquo;<EM>three fundamental purposes</EM>&rdquo; for costs awards: (1) to indemnify successful litigants for the cost of litigation; (2) to encourage settlements; and (3) to discourage and sanction inappropriate behaviour by litigants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 22, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is precisely what the Application Judge did.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Indemnity</EM></TI>
<P>23. The Application Judge held that the hourly rates sought by the respondents were &ldquo;<EM>moderate and reasonable</EM>&rdquo;, and that the allocation of time spent between junior and senior counsel was reasonable, as was the time spent on individual tasks.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraphs 12-13, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The applicants do not challenge these findings. Further:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[14] While the time may at first blush seem high, the respondents have provided a satisfactory explanation for the time involved. They were required to cross-examine the applicants on two occasions because the applicants filed supplementary affidavits substantially changing the basis on which they sought relief, there was extensive delay by the applicants requiring multiple preparation sessions, [and] the respondents had to reconstruct their litigation file from computer records because they had transferred the entire file to the applicants at their request which file the applicants subsequently destroyed</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 14, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>24. Justice Sharpe's statement that legally-trained litigants are &ldquo;<EM>not entitled to costs calculated on the same basis as those of the litigant who retains counsel</EM>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> does <EM>not</EM> establish that a self-represented lawyer cannot claim indemnity based upon her normal hourly rate. It establishes that not all the time spent by a self-represented lawyer is recoverable. The basis of calculation Justice Sharpe had in mind was the model whereby a client receives an account for the total time spent by the lawyer on her matter, and the client then claims a proportion of that sum in costs. However, that model does not comfortably apply to an individual who is both lawyer and client. Justice Sharpe was clear that a lawyer cannot recover for client work, (&ldquo;<EM>the time and effort that any litigant would have to devote</EM>&rdquo;) but can recover for legal work (&ldquo;<EM>the work ordinarily done by a lawyer retained to conduct the litigation</EM>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <EM>Fong</EM> does not say that a trial judge cannot award indemnity for <EM>legal work</EM> measured against an hourly rate, as in the normal course. Instead, it emphasizes the trial judge's discretion to set the &ldquo;<EM>appropriate allowance</EM>&rdquo;, without including <EM>per diems</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 26, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. The Application Judge dealt with the issue of client vs. legal time directly:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[15] The applicants produced a schedule in which they have eliminated large amounts of time of the respondents on the basis that a self-represented lawyer should not recover costs for any tasks performed that a client would typically perform. The time the applicants have eliminated in this regard includes time reviewing application material and preparing responding material. It would be the rare client who reviews application material in sufficient detail to prepare a response and the even rarer a client who actually prepares the response</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraph 15, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>26. The applicants do not challenge this finding. Instead, they advance an argument on indemnity which is implicitly contrary to <EM>Fong</EM>; for this reason, they make only passing reference to that case in their factum. The applicants argue that there <EM>is</EM> a categorical rule concerning the granting of costs to a self-represented lawyer, being that the judge at first instance has some discretion concerning whether costs are awarded, but none with respect to the quantum, which must be &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum, at paragraphs 13&ndash;15 and 26</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They argue that the Application Judge erred by applying the &ldquo;moderate and reasonable&rdquo; standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum, at paragraphs 9(a) and 14</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. The practical result of implementing the applicants' proposed &ldquo;nominal costs&rdquo; rule would be that when the successful party is self-represented, the losing party is immunized from a meaningful costs award, no matter its conduct. The applicants' position is therefore flatly contradictory to Justice Sharpe's holding that &ldquo;<EM>[a] rule precluding recovery of costs, in whole or in part, by self-represented litigants would deprive the court of a potentially useful tool to encourage settlements and to discourage or sanction inappropriate behaviour</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fong</EM>, at paragraph 24, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. The word &ldquo;nominal&rdquo; does not appear in <EM>Fong</EM>. It appears in a Divisional Court case which follows <CASEREF><SOC>Fong, Mustang Investigations Inc. v. Ironside</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2010 ONSC 3444 (Divisional Court), Applicants' Authorities at Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The term was not used in a considered manner, but seems to have been introduced into the decision almost by accident.</P>
<P>29. After setting an action down for trial, Mustang Investigations moved for leave to discontinue the matter against the self-represented Mr. Ironside. Justice Perell of the Superior Court granted leave to discontinue, and held that Ironside was entitled to costs of the motion. Justice Perell invited written submissions on costs, and held that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>If Mr. Ironside does not submit written submissions within 30 days, he shall be paid nominal costs, which I fix at the sum of $5,000.00, all inclusive</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations Inc. v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3110</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paragraph 35, Respondents' Authorities at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>30. Ironside did make written submissions, which Justice Perell dealt with in a subsequent decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations Inc. v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3848</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>,Respondents' Authorities at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Therein, he considered <EM>Fong</EM>, and held Justice Sharpe had not intended that a self-represented litigant must prove lost opportunities for remuneration in order to recover costs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations Inc. v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3848</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paragraphs 12-13, Respondents' Authorities at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It was this holding that would eventually be reversed by the Divisional Court. With respect to the quantum of Ironside's costs, Justice Perell held:
<QUOTE><P><EM>24 Rather than reflecting with mathematical precision the actual costs incurred by the successful litigant, the amount of costs should be fair and reasonable in all the circumstances, which may be determined, in part, by considering the reasonable expectations of the parties, most particularly the unsuccessful party [citations omitted]</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>25 In my opinion, Mustang could reasonable expect to pay costs of approximately $20,000 for counsel fee on a partial indemnity basis for bringing Mr. Ironside before the court and compelling him to respond to the various interlocutory motions, including the very serious matter of having him cited for contempt</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>31. In the result, Justice Perell awarded costs of $21,051.40, all inclusive.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mustang Investigations Inc. v. Ironside</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 3848</CITE><PARANUM>Sup. Ct.</PARANUM></CASEREF> at paragraph 26, Respondents' Authorities at Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The word &ldquo;nominal&rdquo; does not appear in his decision. Mustang appealed this second decision to the Divisional Court.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>2010 ONSC 3444 (Divisional Court), Applicants' Authorities at Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Jennings held:
<QUOTE><P><EM>26 The motions judge was initially of the impression that nominal costs should be fixed at $5,000 inclusive, against which $200 awarded by the Master may be set off, for a net recovery of $4,800</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>27 As I have said, Master Dash, and several trial judges, seem to have interpreted Fong as saying that even in the absence of proof of an opportunity cost, one may assume that because the lay person was involved in the litigation preparing material that might otherwise be prepared by a lawyer, he or she should nevertheless be entitled to nominal costs. With great respect to the Master and those judges, I'm unable to find that the language in Fong permits an award to be made without the self-represented litigant demonstrating that, as a result of the lawyer-like work put in on the file, remunerative activity was foregone. Simply stated, no proof of opportunity cost, no nominal costs available</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. Respectfully, none of the cases referred to by Justice Jennings in the above passage held that a self-represented litigant could obtain only &ldquo;nominal&rdquo; costs, no matter the circumstances. The terms used in these decisions were &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Henderson v. Pearlman</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 149</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paragraph 4, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 9</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> &ldquo;moderate or reasonable&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>White v. Ritchie</SOC><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 2360</CITE></CASEREF> (Commercial List) at paragraphs 20 and 24, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and &ldquo;fair and reasonable&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Huard v. Hydro One Networks Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2002] O.J. No. 4547</CITE></CASEREF> (Master) at paragraph 20, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 7</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Jennings appears to have obtained &ldquo;nominal&rdquo; from Justice Perell's initial decision and then used it where he actually intended &ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;. Subsequent appellate cases have not spoken to this discontinuity in terms.</P>
<P>33. Even if the Application Judge was truly faced with two different standards (&ldquo;moderate&rdquo; or &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo;, per this Court, and &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;, per the Divisional Court), he was bound by the higher authority.</P>
<P>34. Concerning quantum, three of the four cases cited by the applicants (<CASEREF><SOC>Huard v. Hydro One Networks Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>White v Ritchie</SOC></CASEREF>, and <CASEREF><SOC>Henderson v. Pearlman</SOC></CASEREF>) concern self-represented lay litigants, not self-represented lawyers, and so are of no relevance to this motion. In the third case, <EM>Sydney Charendoff</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Sydney Charendoff et al v Alec McLennan and 124155 Ontario Inc. et al</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 7241</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, (&ldquo;<BOLD>Sidney Charendoff</BOLD>&rdquo;), Applicants' Authorities at Tab 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the self-represented lawyer had not provided any evidence of lost opportunity costs<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sidney Charendoff</EM>, at paragraph 14, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. Further, the lawyer was criticized by the court for his approach to the motion, which the court held had led to &ldquo;a <EM>great deal of expense and time [that] could have been saved</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sidney Charendoff</EM>, at paragraph 19, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Even so, the court would have (but for the absence of evidence concerning opportunity costs) awarded the lawyer $3,000 in costs for a straightforward motion to set aside a default judgment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sidney Charendoff</EM>, at paragraph 19, Applicants' Authorities at Tab 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Such an award would be far from &ldquo;nominal&rdquo;. Further, this is a decision of a judge with jurisdiction coordinate to that of the Application Judge. It could not, therefore, limit the discretion of the Application Judge to determine the appropriate costs allowance to be made on the facts before him.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III: ADDITIONAL ISSUES</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>To Sanction Inappropriate Behaviour</EM></TI>
<P>35. The applicants have chosen not to challenge the second basis for the Application Judge's award.
<QUOTE><P><EM>[16] The application and my reasons for dismissing it also bear on the appropriateness of the cost award</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>[...]</EM></P>
<P><EM>[20] Bringing an application that is entirely without foundation is ordinarily the basis for an award of substantial indemnity costs. If there were in fact any time that should be discounted because the respondents were acting as clients (which I am not agreeing there was), the respondents are more than compensated for that in the difference between the partial indemnity costs being awarded and the substantial indemnity award that would, in my view, ordinarily apply to the circumstances</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, at paragraphs 16 and 20, Applicants' Record at Tab 8</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>36. This holding represents a &ldquo;fundamental purpose&rdquo; or basis for the costs award which is independent of straightforward indemnity, and which can itself justify the award. Stated differently, it is an alternative discretionary statement of the award's reasonableness, which should sustain the award even if this Court were to set aside the Application Judge's indemnity analysis.</P>
<P>37. As the applicants have not asserted that this holding is incorrect (their notice of appeal and factum are silent on the point, and they did not appeal the dismissal of the application), the necessary result should be dismissal of the motion.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>38. The respondents request the dismissal of the motion, and costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED BY</P>
<P>&ellip35; Fred Tayar of the Respondents</P>
<P>DATE: May 4, 2018</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
